[1] Malaysia (national)
Date: Sun 8 Feb 2009
Source: New Straits Times [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Sunday/NewsBreak/20090208154531/Article/index_html>


The number of dengue cases nationwide has doubled in the 1st 5 weeks of the
year [2009] compared with the same period last year [2008]. And Selangor
still has the highest number. By 6 Feb [2009], some 6623 cases had been
recorded and 18 people had died. In the same period last year [2008] the
numbers were 3829 cases and 9 deaths.

These worrying numbers have given rise to concern for Selangor,
particularly Hulu Langat district, which has 15 of the 40 hotspots
identified in the state. Last year [2008] Selangor recorded 21 262 cases,
almost half of the 49 335 cases nationwide.

Speaking at an anti-dengue campaign at Taman Taming Jaya in Balakong
yesterday [7 Feb 2009], health minister Datuk Liow Tiong Lai said although
Selangor has shown an increase when compared with last year [2008], since
December the number of cases has dropped by 38 per cent. "Although we are
dealing with worrying numbers overall, this is an encouraging trend. People
need to be quicker in consulting a doctor when they have symptoms. Many
people delay treatment," Liow said. Only 35 per cent of people nationwide
are diagnosed with dengue inside 3 days.

He said the ministry has registered 11 892 volunteers in its Communication
for Behavioural Impact (Combi) programme launched last year [2008]. It is
aimed at turning awareness into community action against dengue. They have
been sent to 585 locations around the country. "We need help from local
councils and residents associations as well. If we had enough machines we
could fog all areas on a weekly basis. But we don't have sufficient
machines or manpower," he said.

Liow said more volunteer groups are needed to combat the disease. The
ministry is willing to support them financially, and help them to acquire
fogging machines and training in their use.

The residents of Taman Taming Jaya, where one person has died of dengue,
had organised a gotong-royong [joint responsibility and mutual cooperation.
- Mod.TY] and launched their "10 Minutes a Week -- Destroy _Aedes_ and
Combat Dengue" campaign. The idea is that volunteers from secondary schools
and non-governmental organisations in the area spend a short time each week
cleaning up the neighbourhood.

[byline: Lydia Gomez]

