[2] Malaysia (Selangor)
Date: Sun 8 Feb 2008
Source: New Straits Times [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/NST/Sunday/National/2473843/Article/index_html>


Some 6240 dengue cases and 16 deaths were recorded up to 4 February this
year [2009], a 55 per cent increase compared with 3407 cases and 9 deaths
recorded in the same period last year [2008], health minister Datuk Liow
Tiong Lai said. However, on a weekly basis, however, the number showed a
decrease, he added.

"A total of 1013 cases with 2 deaths were recorded in the 4th week [2009],
or a 37 per cent drop compared with 1633 cases and 4 deaths in the 1st week
[2009]. There were 1578 cases and 4 deaths recorded in the 2nd week and
1310 cases with 5 deaths in the 3rd week," he stated.

Of the total, 3835 cases and 10 deaths were in the Klang Valley. Liow said
13 of the 54 dengue hotspots identified last month [January 2009] were now
free of the disease. However, dengue had erupted in 3 new localities,
bringing the total number of dengue hotspots to 44 -- 40 in Selangor, 3 in
Kuala Lumpur, and one in Terengganu.

The minister said the ministry was targeting to reduce the number of dengue
cases by 10 000 this year [2009]. Last year [2008], Malaysia recorded about
49 300 cases. He said 94 chikungunya cases were reported nationwide between
[25-31 Jan 2009].

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In addition to Putrajaya, the 3 Feb 2009 edition of the Star
(<http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2009/2/3/central/3171597&sec=central%3E%20&sec=central>)
identified 14 residential areas in Shah Alam, the capital of Selangor
state, as dengue hot spots. Of the reported cases, 161 have been confirmed
with one case of DHF (dengue hemorrhagic fever). Shah Alam City Council
officials have inspected 3252 places, including residential premises,
commercial areas, schools, factories, kindergartens, construction sites,
abandoned housing projects, playgrounds, and other recreational spots
throughout the city. They found _Aedes_ mosquito breeding sites at 240
premises and had issued 137 summonses, which carries a fine of RM 500 [USD
139]. they have also fogged 165 889 premises.

This report was communicated by ProMED-mail rapporteur A-Lan Banks.

Putrajaya is the relatively new seat of government offices and ministries
located to the south of Kuala Lumpur in Selangor state. - Mod.TY]

