[7] Australia (Queensland, prevention)
Date: Sat 7 Feb 2009
Source: The Australian [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25019135-5006786,00.html>


Travelers arriving at Cairns airport should be screened for dengue fever,
an infectious disease specialist said yesterday [6 Feb 2009]. As health
authorities battle the fastest spreading outbreak ever seen, James Cook
University medicine professor James McBride said the Government should
consider installing a thermal scanner to identify dengue fever cases. "If
we can identify everybody that came into the country with dengue [virus],
then we wouldn't have epidemics," professor McBride said.

The clinical microbiologist said although the technology would not stop all
dengue fever outbreaks, it had the potential to reduce the incidence of the
virus. The federal Government last night [6 Feb 2009] dismissed the
suggestion, despite having 25 unused portable scanners purchased in
response to the threat of pandemic influenza, saying current screening was
sufficient.

Cases of the mosquitoborne disease have skyrocketed: last night [6 Feb
2009] there were 279 in Cairns and 49 in Townsville, compared with 170 in
Cairns and 9 in Townsville just a fortnight ago. The potentially fatal
disease also spread to the tourist town of Port Douglas, north of Cairns,
last night with one confirmed case.

Professor McBride said the scanners would identify travellers who had
fevers, one of the main symptoms of dengue fever. The current Cairns
epidemic was started by a traveller from Indonesia. Professor McBride said
12 people with dengue arrived in north Queensland every year.

Taiwan, China, and Hong Kong scan travellers and Canada did so during the
SARS outbreak from late 2002 to mid 2003.

Scott Ritchie, director of medical entomology at Tropical Population Health
Services in Cairns, said the current dengue virus was the most rapidly
moving he had seen. Dr Ritchie said the transmission rate for this form of
virus was as short as 9 days, compared with 17 days during the 2003
outbreak. He said the virus could not be eradicated until winter, when it
would be too dry and too cold for mosquitoes to breed and the virus to spread.

[byline: Sarah Elks]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[Screening incoming travelers for fever would not detect individuals who
were infected with dengue virus, would become viremic, but were not yet
febrile. - Mods.MPP/TY

